# Introduction

------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this chapter we will show you how to take into account the sample
variation when making estimate on a population parameter by using a
sample statistic.

## What is a good estimator?

The behavior the sample mean described in the CLT makes the sample mean
a very good estimator for the population mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

A good estimator should possess two qualities:

-   **Unbiasedness**: the mean of the distribution of the estimator
    should be the value that we want to predict;  
-   **Small Spread**: the spread of the the distribution of the
    estimator should be small.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

1.  Which of the following random variables (X, Y and Z) is the best
    estimator for predicting the value 5?

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Y is the best predictor since its distribution has mean 5 and the its
spread is smaller than that for Z.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Constructing a confidence interval to estimate the population mean

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The CLT gives a relationship between the sample mean and the population
mean that makes the sample mean an attractive estimator for the
population mean when the sample size is large.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

**Point Estimator v.s. Interval Estimator**

We can use the sample mean as a point-estimate for the population mean;
however, it will be better to have interval-estimate and say how
confident you are about that your interval will cover the population
mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Constructing a confidence interval to estimate the population mean

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Case 1a: When the sample size is large and the population SD=<span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is known to us

------------------------------------------------------------------------

We can construct a 90% confidence interval with a sample mean this way
(we will fill in this part in class with some sketch on blackboard):

    qnorm(p = 0.95)  # 1.64
    [1] 1.644854

> (sample\_mean - 1.64 population\_SD/sqrt(sample\_size), sample\_mean +
> 1.64 population\_SD/sqrt(sample\_size))

We use 1.64 here in the formula to display the formula in a more
intuitive way. In your reports you should always use `qnorm(p=.95)`
instead of 1.64 since you **should not hand-code** in any values in your
code.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Recall that if the population has mean <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span> and SD <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> and if the sample size <span
class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span> is large enough then the sample mean
follows a N(mean = <span class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span>, SD =
<span class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\sigma}{n}\\)</span>); thus, about
90% of the sample means fall within 1 SD <span
class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}\\)</span> of the mean
<span class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span>.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Copying the length of the dark blue interval on the previous graph we
can construct confidence interval by using the sample mean as the center
of our confidence interval:

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

A confidence interval constructed this way has 90% chance covering the
population mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

**In general how do we find out the arm length of the confidence
interval required?**

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Recall that in Precept 3 we saw that rescaling the data set is not going
to change the area on the bars of a histogram for the corresponding
intervals.

This can be generalize to probability density curves. Rescaling the data
will not change the area under the density curves for the corresponding
intervals.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

In practice this means that if <span class="math inline">\\(Z\\)</span>
follows Normal(mean=0, SD = 1) and <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span> follows Normal(mean=3, SD = 2). The
probability that Z is between -1 and 2 will be the same as the
probability that Y is between 1 and 7. In both cases, we are trying to
find out the probability that our Normal random variable is between 1 SD
*below* the mean and 2 SDs *above* the mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

If for all the data points of <span class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span>
we subtract 3 (the mean of <span class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span>)
from their values and divide by 2 (the SD of <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span>), the distribution of <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span> will have mean 0 and SD 1; i.e.,
after performing the aforementioned operations on <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span>, the resulting values of <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span> will form a distribution that is the
same as <span class="math inline">\\(Z\\)</span>. Performing the
operations above is called *standardizing* a random variable.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

**Normal(mean=0, SD = 1)** is called the **standard Normal
distribution**. In general if <span class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span>
follows a Normal(mean=<span class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span>, SD =
<span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span>) distribution then the
area under the density curve for <span
class="math inline">\\(Y\\)</span> between <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span> + a <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span> + b <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> where <span
class="math inline">\\(a \\leq b\\)</span> is the same as the area
between a and b under the density for the standard Normal distribution.
Because of this equivalence, we can just use the standard Normal
distribution to find the arm lengths when we already know the <span
class="math inline">\\(SD(\\bar{X})\\)</span>, the SD of the sample
mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **SD and SE**

The SD of an estimator is often called the Standard Error (SE). E.g.,
when we are using a sample mean to estimate a population mean, the SD of
the sample mean distribution is also called SE. Note that **SD and SE
are exactly the same thing**, the only difference is that SE is a name
reserved for estimators!!

<span class="math display">\\\[\\begin{align} & SE(sample\\ mean) =
SD(sample\\ mean) \\\\ = & \\frac{Population\\ SD}{\\sqrt{sample\\
size}} = \\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}} \\end{align}\\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Suppose I have a simple random sample of size 100 and the sample mean is

1.  For a 80% CI, how long does the arm length need to be?

    qnorm(p = 0.9)
    [1] 1.281552

    # The SE(sample mean) is
    5/sqrt(100)
    [1] 0.5

    # The arm length is
    qnorm(p = 0.9) * 5/sqrt(100)
    [1] 0.6407758

------------------------------------------------------------------------

1.  Construct a 80% confidence interval to estimate the population mean

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    c(24.5 - qnorm(p = 0.9) * 5/sqrt(100), 24.5 + qnorm(p = 0.9) * 
        5/sqrt(100))
    [1] 23.85922 25.14078

### How precise is your estimate?

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Note that the arm length of a CI, <span
class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha + \\frac{\\alpha}{2})} SE(\\bar
x)\\)</span>, is called the *margin of error*.

Ideally, we want high confidence with small range for a CI. Once you
construct a (<span class="math inline">\\(1-\\alpha\\)</span>)
confidence interval, varying two quantities will change the arm length
of your CI:

-   <span class="math inline">\\(1-\\alpha\\)</span>;
-   <span class="math inline">\\(SE(\\bar x)\\)</span>.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **Example 1**

<span class="math inline">\\(SE(sample \\ mean) = \\frac{population \\
SD}{\\sqrt{sample \\ size}}\\)</span>. If you increase your sample size
by a factor by 9, the length of your CI will be reduced by a factor of
3:

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\frac{population \\ SD}{\\sqrt{new\\
sample \\ size}} = \\frac{population \\ SD}{\\sqrt{9\\ old\\ sample \\
size}}= \\\]</span>

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\frac{population \\ SD}{\\sqrt{9}
\\sqrt{old\\ sample \\ size}}= \\frac{population \\ SD}{3 \\sqrt{old\\
sample \\ size}}. \\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Warning: When a sampling procedure is biased increasing your sample size
will not reduce the bias in your sampleit will just repeat the same
mistake on a larger scale. E.g., if you are surveying a lot of people
who are not planning to vote, the data in your sample are not going to
produce a good estimate of the voting result. This is an example of
selection bias.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Case 1b: When the sample size is large and the population SD=<span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is unknown

------------------------------------------------------------------------

In the previous case we were given the population SD <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span>; however, in practice
oftentimes we do not know the population distribution and therefore have
also to estimate the population SD <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span>. If the sample size is large we
can just **use the sample SD, s, to substitute the population SD <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span>**. This is justified by the Law
of Large Number.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

To summarize for case 1: we will construct a (<span
class="math inline">\\(1-\\alpha\\)</span>) confidence interval for the
population mean by using one of the formulas below depending on if we
know the population SD or not:

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span>

where <span class="math inline">\\(s\\)</span> is the SD for the sample.

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Case 2: When the sample size is small, <span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is unknown and the *population is normal*

If the sample size is small but we know that the population has a Normal
distribution (in practice, close to being symmetric is usually enough),
instead of the standard normal distribution <span
class="math inline">\\(N(0, 1)\\)</span>, <span
class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\bar{X}-\\mu}{\\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n}}}\\)</span>
follows a t-distribution with degree of freedom = (sample size -1).

------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this case, we will construct a (<span
class="math inline">\\(1-\\alpha\\)</span>) confidence interval this way

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span>

where <span class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span> is the quantile from the t-distribution
with degree of freedom = (sample size -1).

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The only parameter of a t-distribution is the degree of freedom.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

**When the degree of freedom is large, the t-distribution will be very
close to Normal(0, 1)**. This means that when the sample size is large
enough, even though we do not know the population SD, our sample SD
provides a good approximation of the population SD; note that this
property is consistent with the fact that when the sample size is large
the standardized the sample mean follows a distribution that is
approximately Normal(0, 1).

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Exercise

Find the quantiles that capture 80% of the central area under the
density curve for a t-distribution with degree of freedom = 5.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    # t-dist for the quantile corresponding to 80% central area
    qt(p = 0.9, df = 5)
    [1] 1.475884
    # compared with the standard Normal distribution
    qnorm(p = 0.9)
    [1] 1.281552

Thus, for a t-distribution with degree of freedom = 5, 80% of the
central area is between -1.48 and 1.48. Note that 1.48 &gt; 1.28, this
is because the t-distribution has thicker tails.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **Ways to check graphically if a dataset seem to come from a population that is not Normal**

There are two types of graphs that you can use to check the Normality of
a dataset; you should always use both graphs together:

-   Histogram with Normal density curve with mean = sample mean and sd =
    sample sd;
-   qq plot

Histogram with Normal density curve for N(mean = sample mean, sd =
sample sd) superimposed on top.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

Use qq-plot to compare the sample quantiles with the quantile from N(0,

### Case 3: When the sample size is small and the population is *not* Normal

In this case we do not know the distribution of the sample means. We
will use *Bootstrap sampling* to get an approximation of the
distribution of the sample means and use this approximate distribution
to construct a confidence interval to estimate the population mean.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **Basic idea of Bootstrap sampling**

1.  Do not have information about the population distribution other than
    the sample;
2.  need to find out how much the sample mean values vary around the
    population mean (i.e., to get an idea of the spread of the sample
    mean values);
3.  to estimate the relationship between the population mean and the
    sample mean we do the following

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **Steps to construct CIs by using Bootstrap sampling**

Your sample size is <span class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span> and the
sample mean is <span class="math inline">\\(\\bar x\\)</span>.

1.  Use yours sample as a surrogate population; note that the surrogate
    population has population mean <span class="math inline">\\(\\bar
    x\\)</span> and population SD that is the SD of the sample;
2.  draw many many Bootstrap samples of size <span
    class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span> with-replacement from the
    surrogate population;
3.  calculate the Bootstrap sample means for the Bootstrap samples;
4.  use the values of (Bootstrap sample means - surrogate population
    mean) to approximate the distribution of (sample mean - population
    mean);
5.  use the distribution in step 4 to construct a CI.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### **The form of the CI**

A <span class="math inline">\\(1-\\alpha\\)</span> confidence interval
for the population mean is

<span class="math display">\\\[ \[\\bar x - \\delta\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})},\\ \\bar x - \\delta\_{ \\frac{\\alpha}{2}}\]
\\\]</span> where <span class="math inline">\\(\\delta\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\\(\\delta\_{ \\frac{\\alpha}{2}}\\)</span> are the
quantiles of the distribution of (Bootstrap sample means - surrogate
population mean).

Note that if the distribution of the sample means has a long right tail,
the CI will have a long left arm.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### A derivation of the formula when <span class="math inline">\\(\\alpha = 10\\%\\)</span>

Since the distribution of (Bootstrap sample means - surrogate population
mean) is approximating the distribution of (sample mean - population
mean), we have

<span class="math display">\\\[\\begin{align} \\text{90}\\% &\\approx
P(\\delta\_{.05} \\leq \\bar X - \\mu \\leq \\delta\_{.95})\\\\
\\Longleftrightarrow \\text{90}\\% &\\approx P(-\\delta\_{.05} \\geq
\\mu -\\bar X \\geq -\\delta\_{.95})\\\\ \\Longleftrightarrow
\\text{90}\\% &\\approx P(\\bar X-\\delta\_{.05} \\geq \\mu \\geq \\bar
X-\\delta\_{.95})\\\\ \\Longleftrightarrow \\text{90}\\% &\\approx
P(\\bar X-\\delta\_{.95} \\leq \\mu \\leq \\bar X-\\delta\_{.05})
\\end{align}\\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Summary

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Relationship between any Normal Random Variable and a N(0, 1) Random Variable

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For any Normal Random Variable <span class="math inline">\\(X\\)</span>
with certain mean and SD

-   <span class="math inline">\\(Z = \\frac{X-mean(X)}{SD(X)}\\)</span>
    will always result in a stardard Normal Random Variable; i.e., <span
    class="math inline">\\(Z \\sim N(0,1)\\)</span>. The procedure
    described is called standardizing <span
    class="math inline">\\(X\\)</span>.

-   For **N(mean(X), SD(X))** the area under the density curve between
    **mean(X)-aSD(X)** and **mean(X)+bSD(X)**, where a, b &gt;0,
    corresponds to the area under the **N(0, 1)** density curve
    **between -a and b**.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Constructing C.I. (One population case)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

We have learned how to construct confidence intervals to obtain interval
estimates of the population mean (<span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span>) in different scenarios
(population SD will be denoted as <span
class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> and sample SD will be denoted
as s in all scenarios)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

-   **Case 1: When the sample size <span
    class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span> is large:** The standardized
    sample means form a Normal(0, 1) approximately. If the population SD
    <span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is known we can
    calculate the <span class="math inline">\\(SE(\\bar X) =
    \\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}\\)</span> ; if the population SD <span
    class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is unknown, because the
    sample size is large, the sample SD will be a good estimate of the
    population SD, <span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span>. In
    this case, <span class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\bar{x} -
    \\mu}{SE(\\bar{x})} \\approx \\frac{\\bar{x} -
    \\mu}{\\frac{s}{n}}\\)</span> follows <span
    class="math inline">\\(N(0, 1)\\)</span> by the CLT. **We use the
    Normal(0, 1) distribution to find out the value for <span
    class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha +
    \\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span>.**

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span> or

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

-   **Case 2: When the sample size is small, <span
    class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is unknown and the
    *population is normal*:**

If the population SD <span class="math inline">\\(\\sigma\\)</span> is
unknown to us, with the condition that the *population is normal* (or at
least close to being symmetric) the standardized sample means form a
t-distribution with degree of freedom = (sample size -1) = <span
class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span>-1. In this case <span
class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu}{SE(\\bar{x})} \\approx
\\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu}{\\frac{s}{n}}\\)</span> follows <span
class="math inline">\\(t\_{df = n-1}\\)</span> distribution. **Thus, we
will use the t-distribution with degree of freedom <span
class="math inline">\\(n\\)</span>-1 to find out the value for <span
class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span>.**

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

-   **Case 3: When the sample size is small and the population is *not*
    normal:** In this case we do not know the distribution of the sample
    mean nor the distribution of <span
    class="math inline">\\(\\frac{\\bar{x} -
    \\mu}{SE(\\bar{x})}\\)</span>. We will use *Bootstrap sampling* to
    get an approximation of the distribution of <span
    class="math inline">\\(\\bar{x} - \\mu\\)</span> and use this
    approximated distribution to construct a confidence interval to
    estimate the population mean.

# Answer the question posed at the beginning of this section

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Goal: want to estimate the average age of the viewers for the show.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

**For Company N: a sample of the 10,000 viewers:**

-   The average age: 41.29 year old
-   The SD of the ages of the viewers: 10.98

**Tanias sample of size 20:**

    tania = c(49, 35, 54, 64, 46, 34, 44, 42, 36, 34, 28, 48, 46, 
        43, 53, 57, 27, 36, 58, 20)

**Brandons sample of size 20:**

    brandon = c(48, 32, 64, 57, 68, 54, 35, 38, 29, 38, 39, 36, 42, 
        35, 51, 40, 50, 33, 50, 37)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Lets construct a <span class="math inline">\\(90\\%\\)</span> C.I. with
each of the samples!

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For the sample of Company N we are in

(A.) Case 1; i.e., the standardized sample mean <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\\)</span> follows the <span
class="math inline">\\(N(0, 1)\\)</span> distribution approximately;

(B.) Case 2; i.e., the standardized sample mean <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\\)</span> follows the <span
class="math inline">\\(t\_{df = n-1}\\)</span> distribution
approximately;

(C.) Case 3; i.e., we will use Bootstrap sampling to find out what the
interval estimate should be.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For Company N, <span class="math inline">\\(SE(\\bar x) =
\\frac{10.98}{\\sqrt{10000}} = .1098\\)</span>.

a <span class="math inline">\\(90\\%\\)</span> C.I. for the average age
of the viewers has the form

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span> where <span
class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha + \\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span>
can be calculated by

    qnorm(0.95)
    [1] 1.644854

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Thus, a <span class="math inline">\\(90\\%\\)</span> C.I. for the
average age of the viewers is (41.11 41.47) in years.

    c(41.29 - qnorm(0.95) * (10.98/sqrt(10000)), 41.29 + qnorm(0.95) * 
        (10.98/sqrt(10000)))
    [1] 41.1094 41.4706

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For Tania the sample

(A.) Case 1; i.e., the standardized sample mean <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\\)</span> follows the <span
class="math inline">\\(N(0, 1)\\)</span> distribution approximately;

(B.) Case 2; i.e., the standardized sample mean <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\\)</span> follows the <span
class="math inline">\\(t\_{df = n-1}\\)</span> distribution
approximately;

(C.) Case 3; i.e., we will use Bootstrap sampling to find out what the
interval estimate should be;

(D.) Case 2 or 3.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For Tania the sample size (20) is a bit small so we need to check to see
whether it is okay to assume that the population is Normal. In practice,
as long as the population distribution is not too skewed we can just
proceed with the procedure described in case 2.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Investigate the sample data:

    hist(tania, main = 'Age of the 20 viewers in sample',
         xlab = 'Ages (in Years)', freq = F) 
    xseq = seq(from = .9*min(tania), to = 1.1*max(tania), length = 100)
    lines(y = dnorm(xseq, mean = mean(tania), sd = sd(tania)), x = xseq, col = "blue")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    # quantile-quantile plot
    qqnorm(y = tania, main = "Normal Q-Q Plot for Ages (years)", 
        xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles", ylab = "Sample Quantiles", 
        cex.lab = 0.8, cex.main = 0.8)

    qqline(y = tania, col = "blue")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The sample distribution is pretty symmetric, so the standardized sample
mean follows the <span class="math inline">\\(t\_{19}\\)</span>
distribution.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

a <span class="math inline">\\(90\\%\\)</span> C.I. for the average age
of the viewers has the form

<span class="math display">\\\[ \\bar x \\pm \\ q\_{(1-\\alpha +
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})} \\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n} } \\\]</span> where we find the
value for <span class="math inline">\\(q\_{(1-\\alpha+
\\frac{\\alpha}{2})}\\)</span> from the <span
class="math inline">\\(t\_{19}\\)</span> distribution.

    q.tania = qt(0.95, df = length(tania) - 1)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The 90% C.I. using Tanias sample is (38.27, 47.13).

    se.tania = sd(tania)/sqrt(length(tania))
    c(mean(tania) - q.tania * se.tania, mean(tania) + q.tania * se.tania)
    [1] 38.26824 47.13176

------------------------------------------------------------------------

For Brandon the sample size (20) is a bit small so we need to check to
see whether it is okay to assume that the population is Normal.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Investigate the sample data:

    hist(brandon, main = 'Age of the 20 viewers in sample',
         xlab = 'Ages (in Years)', freq = F) 
    xseq = seq(from = .9*min(brandon), to = 1.1*max(brandon), length = 100)
    lines(y = dnorm(xseq, mean = mean(brandon), sd = sd(brandon)), x = xseq, col = "blue")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    # quantile-quantile plot
    qqnorm(y = brandon, main = "Normal Q-Q Plot for Ages (years)", 
        xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles", ylab = "Sample Quantiles", 
        cex.lab = 0.8, cex.main = 0.8)

    qqline(y = brandon, col = "blue")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The sample distribution is a bit skewed, so we will use Bootstrap
sampling to construct the C.I. and compare the result with the C.I.
constructed by using the t-distribution.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Use Bootstrap sampling to get a 90% CI:

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    set.seed(1234)
    # Create Bootstrap samples
    mat = matrix(sample(brandon, size = length(brandon) * 10000, 
        replace = T), ncol = 10000)

    # Calculate the deviations of Bootstrap samples
    mean_pop.deviation = apply(mat, MAR = 2, FUN = mean) - mean(brandon)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" />

------------------------------------------------------------------------

    dev = quantile(mean_pop.deviation, 
                   prob = c(.90+(1-.90)/2, (1-.90)/2))

------------------------------------------------------------------------

A 90% Bootstrap CI for the population mean is (39.85, 47.6).

    mean(brandon) - dev
      95%    5% 
    39.85 47.65 

------------------------------------------------------------------------

With the t-distribution the 90% C.I. is (39.58 48.02).

    q.brandon = qt(0.95, df = length(brandon) - 1)
    se.brandon = sd(brandon)/sqrt(length(brandon))
    c(mean(brandon) - q.brandon * se.brandon, mean(brandon) + q.brandon * 
        se.brandon)
    [1] 39.58014 48.01986

------------------------------------------------------------------------

The two different methods give similar results because the population
where the sample is drawn from is actually Normal (I know this because I
artificially created the population).

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Summary of the results: 90% C.I.s are

-   Company N: (41.11 41.47);
-   Tania: (38.27 47.13);
-   Brandon: (39.85, 47.6).

The true population mean is 41.2 and the population SD is 11.

# Proportion as a population mean

------------------------------------------------------------------------

A proportion is just a special type of average where the data are just
0s and 1s only. Instead of <span class="math inline">\\(\\mu\\)</span>
sometimes we will use <span class="math inline">\\(\\pi\\)</span> to
denote the population proportion (i.e., the population mean).

In case 2 where we have a small sample size we need to check that the
population is approximately Normal before using the t-distribution to
approximate the standardized sample mean distribution; however, it is
impossible for a dataset with only 0 and 1 values that look like a
Normal distribution, so we should just **make sure that the population
distribution is not too skewed; i.e., <span class="math inline">\\(.05
\\leq \\pi \\leq .95\\)</span>**.

# CIs for predicting population mean difference between two populations, population SDs unknown.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Note that for the case where we are dealing with one population, the
C.I. for estimating the population mean has the form

<span class="math display">\\\[ point \\ estimator \\pm \\
q\_{(1-\\alpha + \\frac{\\alpha}{2})} SE(point \\ estimator) \\\]</span>

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Now, for two *independent* populations with population means <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\_1\\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\_2\\)</span>, a (1-<span
class="math inline">\\(\\alpha\\)</span>) CI for predicting <span
class="math inline">\\(\\mu\_1 - \\mu\_2\\)</span> again has this form:

<span class="math display">\\\[ point \\ estimator \\pm \\
q\_{(1-\\alpha + \\frac{\\alpha}{2})} SE(point \\ estimator) \\\]</span>

Just as we would use the sample mean as a point estimate for the
population mean, we will now use the sample mean difference as a point
estimate for the population mean difference.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Suppose <span class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\_1\\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\_2\\)</span> are the sample means for two
*independent* samples drawn from populations 1 and 2 and the populations
are also *independent*. Then, the previous expression can be re-written
as

<span class="math display">\\\[ (\\bar X\_1 - \\bar X\_2) \\ \\pm \\
q\_{(1-\\alpha + \\frac{\\alpha}{2})} SE(\\bar X\_1 - \\bar X\_2)
\\\]</span>

As long as the distribution of each of the <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\_1\\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\\(\\bar X\_2\\)</span> falls in case 1 or 2
described in the one population case we can use t-distribution with
certain df to find <span class="math inline">\\(q\\)</span>. Therefore,
we can use `t.test()` to construct the C.I.s.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

When dealing with two populations, the syntax for the function
`t.test()` takes the form

    t.test(x=..., y = ..., paired = ..., 
    var.equal = FALSE, conf.level = ...)

In addition to `y` and `conf.level` there are two additional input
arguments for `t.test()` that we need to consider.

-   `var.equal` (default value is FALSE): set this equal to be `TRUE`
    only if at least one of your samples is small *and* you have strong
    evidence that the two populations share the same variance. **In most
    cases this should be set to FALSE** and this is what we will do in
    this course.  
-   `paired` (default value is FALSE): set this equal be `TRUE` if the
    two samples are paired. Note that paired samples are not
    independent.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Exercise 2

We randomly select 20 couples and compare the weekly time the husbands
and wives spent on watching TV. The husbands spent 12.3 hours per week
with SD 3.1, and the wives spent 9.4 hours per week with SD 2.7.
Construct a 90% CI for the difference of the mean hours spent on
watching TV between the husbands and wives.

**Question:** Are the two samples independent?

(A.) Yes  
(B.) No

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Answer: No, the two samples are paired since husbands and wives usually
live in the same house and influence the behavior of each others. Note
that paired samples are not dependent, but dependent samples are not
necessarily paired.
